An equilateral triangle is determined by two points in the set $\{A_1, A_2, \ldots A_9\}$ and the third point on the polygon that is equidistant from these two points.  We consider the following cases:

Case 1: The two points in the set $\{A_1, A_2, \ldots A_9\}$ are adjacent.
In this case, there are two possible equilateral triangles, as shown below:

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

pair[] A;
int i;

for (i = 0; i <= 8; ++i) {
  A[i] = dir(40*i);
  dot("$A_" + string(i+1) + "$", A[i], A[i]);
}

draw(A[0]--A[1]--A[2]--cycle,red);
draw(A[1]--A[2]--A[3]--cycle,red);
[/asy]

Case 2: The two points in the set $\{A_1, A_2, \ldots A_9\}$ are not adjacent.
In this case, there are four possible equilateral triangles, as shown below:

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

pair[] A;
int i;

for (i = 0; i <= 8; ++i) {
  A[i] = dir(40*i);
  dot("$A_" + string(i+1) + "$", A[i], A[i]);
}

draw(A[0]--A[2]--A[5]--cycle,red);
draw(A[1]--A[3]--A[6]--cycle,red);
draw(A[2]--A[4]--A[7]--cycle,red);
draw(A[3]--A[5]--A[8]--cycle,red);
[/asy]

Therefore, there are $2 + 4 = \boxed{6}$ distinct equilateral triangles in the plane of the polygon that have at least two vertices in the set $\{A_1, A_2, \ldots A_9\}$.

