First, we count the number of equilateral triangles that have two vertices on a side of the nonagon.  There are $9$ such sides, and for each side, there are $2$ equilateral triangles.

[asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

int i;

draw(dir(0)--dir(40)--dir(80)--dir(120)--dir(160)--dir(200)--dir(240)--dir(280)--dir(320)--cycle);

for (i = 0; i <= 8; ++i) {
  draw(dir(40*i)--dir(40*(i + 2)));
}

label("$A_1$", dir(0), dir(0));
label("$A_2$", dir(40), dir(40));
label("$A_3$", dir(80), dir(80));
label("$A_4$", dir(120), dir(120));
label("$A_5$", dir(160), dir(160));
label("$A_6$", dir(200), dir(200));
label("$A_7$", dir(240), dir(240));
label("$A_8$", dir(280), dir(280));
label("$A_9$", dir(320), dir(320));
[/asy]

Next, we count the number of equilateral triangles that have two vertices on different sides of the nonagon.  There are $\binom{9}{2} = 36$ such pairs of sides, and for each pair of sides, there is exactly one equilateral triangle.

Therefore, the total number of equilateral triangles is $9 \cdot 2 + 36 \cdot 1 = \boxed{54}.$

